    value: 상중(喪中)에 있는 관리를 복(服) 벗기 전에 다시 등용하는 것. 《북사(北史)》 이덕림전(李德林傳)에, “어머니 상을 만나게 되어 백일로 복을 단축하고 탈정(奪情)하여 기복(起復)시켰다[丁母憂 裁百日 奪情起復].” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D004] 주의(注擬) : '
    value: 당(唐)나라의 과거를 뽑는 제도에, 무릇 응시(應試)하여 당선된 자는 상서성(尙書省)에서 먼저 그 성명과 이력을 책에다 두 번째 고사를 거쳐서 관직에 배정하는 것을 주의라 하였다. 《당서(唐書)》 선거지(選擧志)에, “정관(貞觀) 2년에 시랑(侍郞)유림보(劉林甫)가 말하기를, ‘수(隋)나라 제도는 11월로써 과거(科擧)가 시작되어 이듬해 봄에 끝이 났으나 지금은 당선된 자가 많으니 사철에 주의(注擬)하도록 하여 지이다.’ 하였다.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D005] 고량(膏粱) : '
    value: 고(膏)는 살찐 고기를 말한 것이요, 량(粱)은 아름다운 곡식을 말한 것인데, 부귀하는 집안을 이른 것임.
  - key: '[주-D006] 위독[大漸] : '
    value: 병이 위독하다는 뜻임. 《서경》 고명(顧命)에, “아, 병이 크게 번지어 오직 위태하다[嗚呼疾大漸惟幾].” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D007] 유밀(宥密) : '
    value: 《시경》 주송(周頌) 호천유 성명(昊天有成命)에, “밤낮에 천명(天命)을 받은 것이 유밀(宥密)하다[夙夜基命宥密].”라 하였고, 그 주에, “유(宥)는 굉심(宏深)하단 말이고, 밀(密)은 정밀하단 말이라.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D008] 대행(大行) : '
    value: 제왕이 승하한 처음에는 대행(大行)이라 함. 풍속통(風俗通)에, “천자가 붕(崩)하여 시호가 있지 아니하므로 그 명칭을 대행황제(大行皇帝)라 한다.” 하였고, 《주서(周書)》 시법해(諡法解)에, “시호라는 것은 행실의 자취다. 그러므로 큰 행실은 큰 이름을 받고, 세쇠한 행실은 세쇠한 이름을 받는다.” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D009] 태상(太常) : '
    value: 벼슬 이름임. 진(秦)나라가 봉상(奉常)을 만들었고, 한(漢)나라가 태상(太常)으로 이름을 변경하였는데, 구경(九卿)의 하나로 종묘의 예전을 맡았음.
  - key: '[주-D010] 연성(連城) : '
    value: 연성벽(連城璧)을 말한 것임. 《사기》 인상여전(藺相如傳)에, “조(趙)나라 혜문왕(惠文王) 때에 초(楚)나라 화씨(和氏)의 구슬[璧]을 얻었는데, 진소왕(秦昭王)이 그 소문을 듣고 사람을 시켜 조왕(趙王)에게 편지를 보내어 열다섯 성(城)을 줄 터이니, 구슬을 양보하라고 했다.” 하였음. 그래서 뒤에 연성벽이라 칭하게 되었음.
  - key: '[주-D011] 금마(金馬)와 옥당(玉堂) : '
    value: 금마(金馬)는 한(漢)나라 궁문의 이름으로 학사(學士)들이 조명(詔命)을 기다리던 곳임. 옥당은 한대의 궁전 이름. 《한서》 양웅전(揚雄傳)에, “금마문(金馬門)을 거쳐서 옥당(玉堂)으로 올라간다[歷金門上玉堂].” 하였음.
  - key: '[주-D012] 인각(麟閣)에 운대(雲臺) : '
    value: 인각(麟閣)은 한(漢)나라 기린각(麒麟閣)을 말한 것임. 한선제(漢宣帝)가 공신(功臣)곽광(霍光)ㆍ장안세(張安世)ㆍ한증(韓增)ㆍ조충국(趙充國)ㆍ위상(魏相)ㆍ병길(丙吉)ㆍ두연년(杜延年)ㆍ유덕(劉德)ㆍ양구하(梁丘賀)ㆍ소망지(蕭望之)ㆍ소무(蘇武) 등 11명의 상(像)을 그려 기린각의 백상에 걸어 놓았음. 운대(雲臺)는 역시 한(漢)나라 대의 이름인데, 영평(永平) 간에 명제(明帝) 전세의 공신을 추념하여 등우(鄧禹) 등 28명의 장수의 상을 이 대에 그려 놓았음.
english:
  title: Stele Inscription and Preface for the State Duke of Seobyeong, Posthumously Titled Lord Munjong, Left Minister of the State Council, Senior Rank Ninth, Meritorious Servant for Promoting Loyalty and Settling Difficulties
  author: Seo Geojung
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Alas, how can I bear to inscribe this stele for you?

    When I was but fifteen, studying at the House of Learning, you were three years my junior, only twelve years old. Your talents gleamed like mountain peaks; you read books and grasped their essential meaning. You came to study with us, and from that childhood friendship was born—not merely of face-to-face encounter, but of heart speaking to heart. Though years passed and we grew, our bond never weakened. I was fortunate to pass the examinations before you and entered the Hall of Worthies. Four years later you too achieved the degree. Again we became colleagues, serving together in the inner court for more than ten years, and our friendship deepened still further. In my heart, I have long held this truth: those who gave me life are my parents, but you—you who truly knew me—were as a parent to my spirit. Now you have departed. Ah, the pain of it!

    Your orphaned children came to me with tears, saying: "No one knew our father as you did. Please inscribe his memory so his virtue may never fade. In this we place all our hope." I wept at their words. How could I refuse?

    Now I record: Your surname was Han, your name was Gyexi, your courtesy name was Zishun. The Hans are an ancient clan of Cheongju, tracing their line back to an ancestor named Ran, a minister of the Three Han kingdoms. Through generations they preserved their honor. One ancestor named Ak served King Chungsuk of Goryeo, rose to Prime Minister, and received the posthumous name of Sasuk. He fathered the Lord of Cheongseong, named Gongui, titled Pyeongjian. From him came the Grand Commandant and Director of the Right Library, named Sou, celebrated for both scholarship and virtue, honored as Mungyeong. From him came the Right Minister of State, named Sanggyeong, titled Munjian. From him came the Regional Inspector of Hamgyeongdo, named Hye—your father, whose years were fewer than his virtue deserved, yet he left a legacy of goodness to his heirs.

    Your mother, the Lady of Chunggyeong, of the Seongsing clan, was also a family of distinction from Changnyeong—daughter of the Prince of the Central Hub, Dal. In the ninth month of Yeongnae's gyeungmyo year, on the day of ulsa, she bore you into this world.

    From birth you were marked by exceptional gifts. Your nature was grave and measured, you did not laugh or speak carelessly, your movements aligned naturally with propriety—you seemed already a man grown. As you matured, you loved learning so deeply that hunger and sleep meant nothing to you. In the jeongdong year of the Zhengtong era, you passed the civil service examinations, entered the National Academy, and there you questioned wise teachers and worthy friends about all that puzzled you, never resting until you had penetrated to the very root of things. Your understanding grew ever deeper, your learning ever more refined. Your peers held you in highest regard.

    In jeongmyo you passed the higher examinations and were appointed Rectifier of Characters in the Bureau of Continuing Literature. Soon you were selected for the Hall of Worthies, then promoted through positions of Drafter and Keeper of the Seal, while regularly serving as Lecturer in the Classics. Rising again, you became Vice-Rectifier of the Chancellery. During these years, the great king took great interest in books. He established a Library Pavilion and gathered writings from every region under heaven, filling its chambers to bursting. You spent your leisure hours reading ceaselessly—there was no book you had not studied. With such vast and profound learning, you were compared by many to the great scribe Shinan. When colleagues gathered in free moments, they would discourse brilliantly on novel ideas, each displaying their literary talents. Yet you alone sat upright with composed countenance, a single scroll in hand, your mind absorbed in thought, offering no witty rejoinders. The entire assembly stood in reverence. Can one not see in this a mind so anchored that it does not waver toward distraction?

    When the great king still dwelt in his private quarters, he perceived your excellence and held you in highest esteem. When he ascended the throne in the year ulhai, his favor toward you was exceptional. The Prince of Hoekan was then in the Eastern Palace, and the sovereign commanded you to be his tutor, appointing you Gentleman of Letters to the Crown Prince. In the summer of byeongja you were promoted to Left Counselor of the Crown Prince, receiving the rank of Middle Counselor. In winter you were appointed Executive of the State Censorate. In the spring of jeongchuk you were transferred to Direct Keeper of the Esoteric Pavilion and Keeper of the Seal, also serving as Recorder of the Spring and Autumn Annals. In autumn you moved to Right Virtuous Counselor to the Crown Prince, your posts in the Hall remaining unchanged.

    When the young king ascended to be Heir Apparent, the sovereign again commanded you to serve alone as Reader in the Inner Chambers, rendering immense service. In the first moon of muin you were granted the rank of Principal Counselor and promoted to Minister of War. Soon you rose to Counselor. In the ninth moon you suffered the loss of your father. Though you had lost him early in life, you served your mother with such filial devotion and brought such honor to her that her heart was gladdened. Through your prominence she received rank and repeated honors from the court, bringing glory to your entire clan. When she passed, you mourned with complete observance of rites.

    In the gyeongsin year you were recalled to serve as Right Vice-Director of the Chancellery during your period of mourning. When you could not refuse, you were transferred in the spring of sinsa to Left Vice-Director. In autumn you rose to Counselor and Vice-Minister of Works. Soon you moved to Vice-Director of the Central Chancellery. In the summer of imago you transferred to Vice-Minister of Personnel and Right Deputy Aide to the Crown Prince. One day the sovereign fell ill and commanded you to attend him. As the young king was still of tender years, all matters concerning the succession were placed entirely in your hands—even the royal relatives and inner attendants were kept from knowledge of these affairs. You personally prepared his medicines, and when the sovereign recovered, he bestowed upon you repeated and generous rewards.

    In gyemi you were appointed Governor of Inshun Prefecture. The sovereign, seeing that your learning was profound and your devotion to duty unwavering, entrusted to you the compilation and editing of all classical texts and imperial precedents. Day by day you labored with utmost care. Yet illness visited you repeatedly, bringing you to the very brink of death. The sovereign grew deeply troubled and personally composed prayers on your behalf. When you recovered enough to be received in the private chambers, he spoke to you thus: "You show concern for my welfare, and I show concern for your complexion. I have been ill, and you have always come to my aid. Now that you are ill, I too am grieved. My grief runs so deep that I did not wish even to hear your name spoken. Yet heaven has permitted me to see your face again." His words of comfort were most earnest. Such was the depth of his imperial favor toward you.

    In eulyu you were elevated to Minister of Personnel and promoted to the rank of State Counselor. You submitted a memorial saying: "Your servant, lacking in ability, has been entrusted with the selection of officials. Though I keep my doors open to receive all gentlemen, in discerning the worthy from the unworthy I fear I am yet insufficient. How much more so now, when we have established the system of seniority and forbidden ambitious competition—is this not like asking one who is blind and deaf to distinguish sounds and colors? I beg to be relieved of this burden." The sovereign replied: "Your words are just. Yet the king establishes laws for ten thousand generations. If all who follow you were like you, it would suffice; but without someone like you, it cannot be done." In the summer you were granted the rank of Senior State Counselor.

    While you held the ministry, all whom you appointed were scrupulously chosen with utmost impartiality. You repressed those seeking advancement through improper means and elevated only the worthy of your age. When courtiers sometimes sought positions for their relatives, you did not harshly refuse, saying: "The ancients taught that in recommending others we need not exclude our own kin. If a man's relatives are virtuous, the one who recommends them commits no excess, and the ruler who employs them acts without bias. To exclude someone merely because he comes from a wealthy household, showing even a trace of concern for propriety, would betray ignorance of the true principles of selecting officials." Thus you made your judgments based on merit alone, earning the deep respect of all. Yet you showed no private favoritism to old friends, and your household remained austere, untouched by improper influence. The public discourse praised your impartiality.

    In byeongsu you received the rank of Senior Grade, yet you repeatedly petitioned to resign, saying that the ministry was too great a burden to hold indefinitely. The sovereign said: "The selection of officials is no light matter. Without you, none can manage it properly. I will not hear your resignation." In jeonghai you transferred to the Central Chancellery as Minister. In summer the rebel Yi Si-ae stirred up rebellion in the northeast, killing regional commanders and magistrates, seizing Kilju in revolt. He also plotted against the great ministers at court, spreading rumors that reached the sovereign's ears—and your name was among those mentioned. The sovereign called together his officials to discuss measures. Those who had been implicated withdrew to their private residences to await judgment. Yet you knew nothing of this and entered with the others, whereupon an eunuch stopped you at the threshold. You hesitated and dared not advance further. The sovereign smiled and said to you: "Why have you come so late?" He commanded you to join the council, and kept you within the palace for more than a month before sending you home.

    Your loyalty and integrity had long been manifest, so even in circumstances of such danger and suspicion, you retained the sovereign's complete trust. From this time forward you constantly dwelt in the innermost councils, advising and assisting in all matters. When at last the principal rebel was brought to justice and the region pacified, your strategic counsel had played no small part.

    In the eighth moon of mushu the sovereign fell gravely ill. He summoned you to attend him. After several tens of days his condition became critical. The Crown Prince remained at his bedside, and the sovereign spoke to him thus: "In my heart I have long wished to compose instructions like those of my ancestors and pass them to you. Now that I can no longer do so, I will speak the essentials. First: revere heaven and serve the spirits. Second: honor your ancestors and cultivate filial piety. Third: practice frugality and love your people. Take these to heart and do not abandon my last words." He then commanded you to convey his final instructions to the Crown Prince. The Prince knelt and received them with reverence. The sovereign then spoke to you: "I know the depths of your loyalty. I command you to support my young son. Do not forget the child I leave behind, for he too will not forget you. Thus may you be of mutual benefit." In the ninth moon, as the sovereign's condition grew grave, he summoned you and revealed his intention to transfer the throne. You responded: "This is a matter of utmost importance. I beg that Your Majesty not trouble yourself with such concerns, but rather keep your spirit calm and well-ordered." The sovereign raised his voice twice in emphasis, commanding you to fetch the great seal and imperial robes and present them to the Crown Prince. The Prince knelt, bowed, and received them. He emerged to the main gate, where he received the homage of all the officials. The next day the sovereign ascended to heaven.

    From the time the sovereign first fell ill until the transfer of the throne, circumstances were most tumultuous and urgent. Yet you moved through all these events, coordinating with those about the sovereign, bringing harmony to every matter. Could anyone but one possessed of your steadfast loyalty have accomplished this? One day the officials gathered to decide upon a temple name for the deceased sovereign. The young king commanded you to instruct them, saying: "The virtue and accomplishments of the former sovereign are too great to be captured in merely one or two characters. I wish to select seven or eight characters for the temple name." When the Vice-Minister of Rites Park Won-hyeong proposed adding only two characters, the sovereign grew angry and demanded: "Who proposed this? Who seeks to thwart my intention?" The officials dared not speak. Yet you came forward, saying: "This servant has misunderstood Your Majesty's command, which is why this proposal has arisen. The fault lies with me." At this the sovereign's anger subsided. See how your humility and self-effacement were manifested!

    Before these events, you had secretly memorialized that the Lord of Guseong should not control the imperial guard, as he was of royal blood, and that Nam Yi should not be given command of armies, as his nature was coarse and violent. The sovereign heeded your counsel and removed them both that very day. When the young king ascended the throne, Nam Yi and his confederates indeed attempted treason and were executed. The Lord of Guseong was also removed from his titles. You were honored with the rank of Meritorious Servant for Promoting Loyalty and Settling Difficulties, received an iron decree, and were enfeoffed as Lord of Seobyeong.

    In the spring of gichwuk you received the rank of Senior Grade. In the eleventh moon of that winter the young king ascended to heaven, and the present sovereign inherited the throne. You shared in the merit of stabilizing the succession. In gyeongiin you took additional responsibility for oversight of the Classics Lecturers. In sinmyo you were granted the title of Meritorious Servant for Pure Sincerity, Bright Understanding, Economic Acumen, and Lateral Assistance. In musul you were appointed Left Minister of State Council.

    After your middle years, illness became your constant companion. Your form grew thin and diminished. You repeatedly requested leave to rest and preserve your spirit. You always maintained humility, as if the honors of office held no appeal for you. Your noble character and generous spirit were beyond compare. In the seventh moon of imiin your illness grew severe and you repeatedly sought to resign. You were then enfeoffed as Lord of Seobyeong. On the intercalary eighth moon, on the day ulyu, you passed away in your home. When news reached the sovereign, he was deeply grieved, suspending court proceedings and the markets. He increased the offerings sent to your family beyond the usual measure. The Director of Ancestral Rites conferred upon you the posthumous name of Lord Munjong.

    Your nature was grave and your character pure. Your conduct was virtuous and your resolve steadfast. Throughout your life, inspired by the ancients, you held yourself to the highest standard. Your learning was refined, your understanding elevated. All that issued from your words and appeared in your counsel bore the marks of clarity and rectitude, unmarred by any flaw. In office you upheld public duty and maintained rectitude. In personal conduct you preserved cleanliness and integrity. When conversing with others, you led with humility, never displaying exceptional virtue or superior bearing. Yet when great matters demanded decision, your judgment could not be swayed. At home you lived with utmost frugality, denying yourself even simple comforts. Your ears never heard music, your eyes never gazed upon powder and rouge. Your chamber held only books, its atmosphere as quiet as the mist. You enjoyed the knowledge and favor of our great king—a fortune rare in a thousand years. Yet the greater his favor, the smaller your heart became; the higher your position, the lower your spirit. As successive sovereigns honored and favored you, their kindness never diminished, and you preserved your name and integrity, completing your course with honor.

    Ah, how splendid was your life! In the tenth moon of this year, on the day gyeongiin, your remains were laid to rest on Yeongjangsang Mountain, east-facing, in the southern village of Gwangju, together with your wife, the Lady of Cheonggyeong, of the Lu clan—the same cemetery but separate graves. Your wife had passed away twenty-seven years before you. She was the daughter of the Vice-Minister of Revenue Lu Gye, posthumously honored.

    You fathered four sons: Samun, Gentleman of Rank, Governor of Ganghwa; Samuk, Gentleman of Rank, Secretary of Military Supplies; Sashin, Director of the Office of Brevity; and Sagae, Court Official, Official of the Robe Bureau. You had one daughter who married Yi Yong-hee, Governor of Cheonan. You had two sons by concubines: Sachoe and Sajun. The Governor of Ganghwa married the daughter of Vice-Prefect Gim Sunghai and fathered a daughter who married Vice-Colonel Won Yeo. He later married the daughter of the posthumously-titled Marquis of Matsong Yi-jeon and fathered another daughter, still young. The Secretary married the daughter of County Magistrate Byeon Bo and fathered three sons and one daughter. The eldest son is Seungyeon, the next is Yeonyeon, the rest still young. The Director married the daughter of Keeper of Records Yi Jeong-gyeon and fathered three sons, all still young. The Court Official married the daughter of Vice-Prefect Yi Yu-in and fathered two sons, both still young. The Governor of Cheonan fathered three sons—Chang-in, Chang-ui, and Chang-ye—and three daughters. One daughter married Scholar Bak Hui, one married Official Chen Su-yun, one married Censor An Tang. Vice-Colonel Won Yeo fathered two daughters, still young. Chang-in married the daughter of Vice-Director of the National Academy Choe Gyeong-ji and fathered children, both still young.

    Ah, Lord Seobyeong, to have come to this! How can I inscribe your stele?

    The inscription reads:

    The heavens and earth give forth beauty,
    The stars and mountains gather their essence.
    From this sacred conjunction is born
    A great man—the Lord of Seobyeong.

    Like ice placed in jade vessels
    Was your clarity and refinement,
    Like pearls strung in a connected necklace of cities,
    Your worth beyond measure.

    You rose above all people
    Like the phoenix and the qilin,
    You were an omen for the age
    Like the auspicious star and rainbow clouds.

    Your heart was open as the sky after storm,
    Clear as moonlight after rain.
    You penetrated to the mysteries of principle,
    Reaching to heaven's root and moon's cavern.

    Good fortune found you,
    You achieved eminence,
    Through golden gates and jade halls
    And through encounter—the unicorn pavilion and clouds of state.

    You exercised your talents,
    Your methods were applied,
    With loyalty and diligence,
    You advanced both deed and virtue.

    Why does heaven not preserve
    The pillar of our nation?
    Yet your covenant remains
    Bound with earth—you live beyond death.

    Your sons and grandsons endure,
    Their line flourishing and spreading.
    On the broad plain where the pines grow dense,
    Before the grave standing dark,

    There rises this noble monument—
    Let its fame echo through the ages.
  footnotes:
    - The Hall of Worthies (Jiphyeonjeon) was the premier research and literary institution of Joseon, housing the kingdom's greatest scholars.
    - The author, Seo Geojung, was himself a towering intellectual figure and one of the most celebrated writers of his age. His relationship with Han Gyexi spanned from childhood friendship through decades of collaborative service in the royal courts.
    - The Classics Lecturers (gyeong-yeon-gwon) were senior officials responsible for the education of princes and the king, serving as intellectual advisors to the throne.
    - The internal politicking and succession crises mentioned—particularly the episodes involving Yi Si-ae's rebellion and the transfer of the throne—were pivotal moments in early Joseon history that tested the loyalty of the realm's most trusted officials.
